'''Tar-Atanamir''' (pron. {{IPA|[aˈtanamir]}}) was the thirteenth [[King of Númenor]].<ref name=Tar-Atanamir/>

==History==
Tar-Atanamir succeeded his father, [[Tar-Ciryatan]], and ruled for 192 years, from {{SA|2029}} until his death, being the first King to rule for life since [[Elros|Tar-Minyatur]].<ref name=Tar-Atanamir/>

He was proud and greedy like his father. During his reign the Númenóreans exacted heavy tributes from the men of the coasts of Middle-earth. In his time the Shadow fell upon Númenor and the king and those that followed his opinion spoke openly against the [[Ban of the Valar|ban that forbade them to sail to Tol Eressea and Aman]] and the [[Doom of Men|mortality of Men]], but they still kept their wisdom and feared and did not defy the [[Valar]].<ref name=Tar-Atanamir/> It was then when the people started being divided into the [[King's Men]] and the [[Faithful]].<ref>{{App|Numenor}}, paragraph about king Tar-Atanamir, p. 1036</ref>

During his reign the [[Eldar]] reported to the [[Valar]] that the [[Númenóreans]] were beginning to speak against the Ban of the Valar. Aggrieved, [[Manwë]] sent messengers to Tar-Atanamir. They explained that even if the Númenóreans could find the way to [[Aman]] it would not undo [[Gift of Men|their doom]]. Tar-Atanamir brought up the matter of his ancestor [[Eärendil]] who still lived in the sky, but according to the messengers his was a fate apart. Atanamir was unsatisfied that he and his people must abide the will of [[Ilúvatar|Eru]].<ref>{{S|Akallabeth}}</ref>

He was known as "the Great", and also "the Unwilling", because he was the first King of [[Númenor]] that refused to give up his life and the [[Sceptre of Númenor]] to his heir. He lived on into old age and senility.<ref name=Tar-Atanamir/> Thus he begun a new tradition as every of his successors did not relinquish his reign until death.<ref>{{UT|Kings}}, entries XIV to XXV</ref>

He was succeeded by his son, [[Tar-Ancalimon]].<ref name=Tar-Ancalimon/> [[Herucalmo]], the husband of queen [[Tar-Vanimeldë]], also was descended from Tar-Atanamir.<ref name=Tar-Vanimelde/>

== Etymology ==
''Atanamir'' is a [[Quenya]] name. Its meaning is not glossed, but Paul Strack suggests it means "Man Jewel" from ''[[atan]]'' ("Man") and ''[[mírë]]'' ("jewel", "gem", "precious thing", "treasure", "precious").<ref>{{webcite|author=Paul Strack|articleurl=https://www.eldamo.org/content/words/word-1357909571.html|articlename=Q. ''Atanamir'' m.|website=Eldamo|accessed=23 December 2021}}</ref> Like all the rulers of Númenor who took their royal names in Quenya, Atanamir added the prefix ''tar-'' ("high") to his name when he received the [[Sceptre of Númenor|Sceptre]].<ref>{{UT|Kings}}, first paragraph and entry I to XXV</ref>

